k, England"},"en":{"about 1078–23 February 1129":"about 1078–23 February 1129","1078–1129":"1078–1129","1084–1148":"1084–1148","1114–1166":"1114–1166","–Male":"Deceased","1042–1129":"1042–1129","1058–1153":"1058–1153","1153":"1153","1086":"1086","1042":"1042","1096":"1096","23 February 1129":"23 February 1129","1084":"1084","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1148":"1148","1114":"1114","1058":"1058","1166":"1166","1078":"1078","about 1078":"about 1078","Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire, England":"Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire, England","Stopsley, Bedfordshire, England":"Stopsley, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Litcham, Mitford, County Norfolk, England":"Mitford, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Knight","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status or occupational name from Middle English <i>knight</i> ‘retainer, attendant’ (Old English <i>cniht</i> ‘boy, youth, lad)’. The specialized feudal sense ‘a high-ranking tenant bound to serve his lord as a mounted soldier’ is not known to have ever given rise to the surname, although it is not out of the question that it may occasionally have been used as a nickname, perhaps for someone who played the part of an armed knight in a local pageant.","Irish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the knight’. See also   McKnight  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Knights","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Knight  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"McKnight","meanings":["Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an Ridire</b> ‘son of the horseman (Gaelic <i>ridire</i>)’, formerly Anglicized <i>McRuddery</i>.","Scottish (Dumfriesshire and Galloway) and Irish (Ulster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Neachtain</b>, which is usually Anglicized as   McNaughton  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Simon  , now rare, but more common in the Middle Ages, when it gave rise to the surnames <i>Simms</i> and <i>Simpson</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Simon","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hoo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern informal short form of names such as   Rupert   and   Ruth .  In  A. A. Milne's  Winnie the Pooh, Roo is the name of the irrepressible child of Kanga, whose name therefore represents the second element of the word <i>kangaroo</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":8,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":18,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":28,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Hoo Knight was born about 1078, in Stopsley, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas de Hoo, was 37 and his mother, Princess Ann Verch Gruffydd I of Flintshire, was 21. He had at least 2 sons with Milicina Princess of Malmaynes. He died on 23 February 1129, in Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52, and was buried in Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire, England."},"et":{"about 1078–23 February 1129":"umbes 1078–23. veebruar 1129","1078–1129":"1078–1129","1084–1148":"1084–1148","1114–1166":"1114–1166","–Male":"Surnud","1042–1129":"1042–1129","1058–1153":"1058–1153","1153":"1153","1086":"1086","1042":"1042","1096":"1096","23 February 1129":"23. veebruar 1129","1084":"1084","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1148":"1148","1114":"1114","1058":"1058","1166":"1166","1078":"1078","about 1078":"umbes 1078","Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire, England":"Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire, England","Stopsley, Bedfordshire, England":"Stopsley, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom